#!/usr/bin/perl

use bom;
use bom::txn;
use bif;
use Getopt::Long;
use Data::Dumper;

my %claim;
my $denom;

while (my $line = <DATA>) {
  $denom = $1 if ($line =~ /^Claim ID: +(.*)/);
  $claim{$denom} .= $line;
}

sub usage {
  print STDERR "Usage: fx_import [-d db_directory] [-h host] acct\n";
  exit 1;
}

$options{'d'} = "/usr/local/barter/db";
$options{'h'} = "localhost";
GetOptions(\%options, 'd=s', 'h=s') == 1 or usage;
my $acctid = shift(@ARGV) or usage;
@ARGV and usage;

bom_db_init($options{'d'});

sub fatal {
  print STDERR "$0: @_";
  bom_db_exit;
  exit 1;
}

my $acct = new bom::acct $acctid;

try_txn {
  $acct->exists or fatal "acct $acct does not exist.\n";
  $acct->read;
} catch {
  fatal "database error (\$acct->read): $_\n";
  death;
};

my $client = new bif::client $options{'h'};
$client->connected or fatal "cannot connect to $options{'h'}\n";

try {
  $client->authenticate($acct);
} catch {
  fatal "authentication error.\n";
};

try {
  while (my ($denomid, $promise) = each(%claim)) {
    my $denom = new bom::denom $denomid;
#print $denom->id . "\n";
    print encode_string($promise) . "\n\n";
    $client->denom_create($denom);
    $client->denom_set($denom, 'promise', $promise);
  }
} catch {
  fatal "server-side error\n";
};

bom_db_exit;
exit 0;

__DATA__
Claim ID:      10000
Creation Date: 1999/02/28
Due Date:      2000/01/10

 a YES coupon shall pay FX$.01 for each 20 points above 10000 of the
 last published closing value for the Dow Jones Industrial Average for 
 the year 1999, rounded to the nearest cent, but shall not pay more
 than $1. A DJIA value below 10010 will cause YES coupons to expire
 worthless.

Claim ID:      1040
Creation Date: 1995/05/02
Due Date:      2001/05/01

 
    On 4/15/2001, the U.S. tax system will still have _all_ of the
    following features:
     1. _multiple brackets:_ there will be at least three different
        marginal tax rates; which one is applied depends on the quantity
        and type of income
     2. _marriage penalty:_ all else being equal, there exist cases where,
        for N < 200000, a husband and wife, each of whom earns N dollars,
        pays more in federal income taxes than two single people, each
        earning N dollars
     3. _income sources:_ wages, interest, dividends, and capital gains
        from investments will all be considered taxable income
     4. _withholding:_ employers must withhold estimated income taxes from
        wages paid to their employees
     5. _mortgage interest deduction:_ at least some of the interest paid
        on home mortgages will be deductible from income
     6. _no national sales tax/VAT:_ there will be no additional
        *national* sales tax or "value added tax" imposed on non-luxury
        goods sold at retail. (Taxes already in existence on 4/15/1995
        don't count here).
        
    Note that changes in individual tax rates, bracket boundaries, or
    exemption/deduction amounts do not count as "changes" since they do
    not affect the deep structure of the tax system.

Claim ID:      13Gy
Creation Date: 1995/09/07
Due Date:      TBD

 
   The Claim
   
    The universe is older than 13 Giga years. YES coupons pay $1 if and
    when it is judged that measurements of cosmological and astrophysical
    parameters lead to a calculated age for the universe greater that 13.0
    billion years at the 95% confidence level. NO coupons will likewise
    pay $1 if and when a calculation gives an age of less than 13.0
    billion years at 95% confidence. If any measurement essential to the
    calculation remains controversial the judge must wait for independent
    confirmation. If some other calculation contradicts the result then
    judgement cannot be made until the discrepancy has been resolved to
    the satisfaction of the majority of professional astronomers. The
    judge will base his decision on published papers and preprints, and on
    acceptance of the results by a majority of cosmologists and
    astrophysicists.
    
   Clarification
   
    The age of the universe is defined as the largest possible value of
    proper time integrated along a timelike geodesic from the Earth at the
    present epoch back to the big bang. In performing the calculation of
    the universe's age it is acceptable to assume that general relativity
    and other well established physical theories are correct and that the
    universe is effectively homogeneous and isotropic at large scales
    (unless there is significant evidence to the contrary). Uncertainty
    due to effects of quantum gravity can be assumed to be insignificant.
    It is not acceptable to assume that the cosmological constant is zero
    or make any other assumptions about cosmological parameters, such as
    matter density, without taking into account uncertainty in their
    measured value or limits. It is not acceptable to make unsupportable
    extrapolations or to rely on fine tuning arguments. It is not
    acceptable to make assumptions based on theories which are not well
    established such as the cosmological inflation theory (unless they
    become well established by time the claim is judged). If the theory
    that the big bang never happened becomes widely accepted by
    professional astronomers and the universe is thereby shown to be
    infinitely old then YES coupons pay. However, in a theory of a cyclic
    universe in which each cycle begins with a big bang, or a universe in
    which the big bang was a local incident in an older universe the age
    of the universe will still be taken as its age since the big bang. If
    it is shown that the universe is exactly cyclic with no big bang and
    the cycle time is less than 13 Gy or if any other accepted theory
    makes the meaning of the claim ambiguous then pay-out is split 50/50
    between YES and NO.
    
   Background
   
    Controversy surrounds two contradictory indications of the age of the
    universe. On the one hand, many measurements of the Hubble constant
    (most notably that based on observations by the Hubble Space Telescope
    on the galaxy M100 in the Virgo Cluster) suggest an age of the
    universe of between 8 and 12 Gy. On the other, astrophysicists compute
    the age of stars in globular clusters to be about 14 to 16 Gy. The
    claim will not be settled until this controversy has been resolved.
    
   Further Information
   
    Hubbles Constant and the Age of the Universe at
    [1]http://www.mathsoft.com/astronomy/hubble.html
 
 References
 
    1. http://www.mathsoft.com/astronomy/hubble.html

Claim ID:      1wgov
Creation Date: 1996/08/18
Due Date:      2100/01/01

 
    World government established before 2100. A single government
    structure/body will control/be responsible for at least 75% of the
    world population. To be considered a World Government, _all_ of the
    following must be true:
     1. At least 75% of the world population is directly represented by,
        controlled by, and/or is the responsibility of the world
        government.
     2. The world government will directly control the largest force of
        military/police personnel and equipment. The force will be larger
        than any subordinate member nation-state controlled militia.
     3. The world government will have the power to levy taxes, impose
        tariffs (if there are independent nations outside the world
        government), and regulate commerce.
     4. The world government will have the power to pass and enforce laws
        on all its population, in all its constituent states.

Claim ID:      2KIRA
Creation Date: 1998/07/12
Due Date:      2001/04/16

 
    The U.S. federal government will, for a period of no less than 90
    consecutive days prior to April 15, 2001, either:
    1) ban premature distributions (sometimes called early withdrawals or
    early distributions) from Individual Retirement Accounts,
    2) require a waiting period of 90 days or more between the date of
    request for a premature distribution from an Individual Retirement
    Account and the date on which the assets withdrawn are made available
    to the requestor, or
    3) increase the additional (penalty) tax on a premature distribution
    from an Individual Retirement Account to a rate of 30% or more. This
    claim refers to Individual Retirement A_ccount_s, which are one, but
    not the only, type of Individual Retirement A_rrangement_.
    
    For purposes of this claim, "Individual Retirement Account" has the
    meaning defined in IRS Publication 590, Individual Retirement
    Arrangements (IRAs); Chapter 2 - When and How Can an IRA Be Set Up?,
    "Kinds of IRAs", "Individual Retirement Account" as of July 1, 1998.
    
    As of July 1, 1998, the additional tax on premature distributions from
    Individual Retirement Accounts is 10%.
    
    Notes: This claim refers to a potential US government action to
    prevent a run on banks. It is one of many emergency actions the US
    government might use to cope with effects of Year 2000 (Y2K) computer
    problems. However, no part of the claim depends on whether a Y2K
    problem occurs or whether any of the events listed in the claim
    description is related to a Y2K problem. The claim owner expects that,
    for various reasons, people and organizations will be reluctant, or
    refuse, to admit that Y2K problems are among the causes of or reasons
    for some events.
    
    References:
    
    "A Glitch in Time"
    [1]http://www.salonmagazine.com/21st/books/1998/03/cov_02books.html
    Edward Yourdon mentions possible IRA withdrawal prevention and penalty
    in the middle of page 3 of this article.
    
    IRS Publication 590, Individual Retirement Arrangements (IRAs);
    Chapter 2 - When and How Can an IRA Be Set Up?, "Kinds of IRAs",
    "Individual Retirement Account"
    [2]h ttp://www.irs.ustreas.gov/plain/forms_pubs/pubs/p5900201.htm
    
    IRS Publication 590, Individual Retirement Arrangements (IRAs);
    Chapter 6 - What Acts Result in Penalties?, "Premature Distributions
    (Early Withdrawals)"
    [3]h ttp://www.irs.ustreas.gov/plain/forms_pubs/pubs/p5900603.htm
 
 References
 
    1. http://www.salonmagazine.com/21st/books/1998/03/cov_02books.html
    2. http://www.irs.ustreas.gov/plain/forms_pubs/pubs/p5900201.htm
    3. http://www.irs.ustreas.gov/plain/forms_pubs/pubs/p5900603.htm

Claim ID:      2e6Pri
Creation Date: 1999/04/07
Due Date:      2000/02/01

 A prime number of at least 2 million decimal digits will be
 discovered, and confirmed by reputable third party, on or before 31
 december 1999. 
 
 The claim will be considered confirmed if reported in the popular
 press such as Scientific American, Science, Nature, or any of the
 well known mathematical journals.

Claim ID:      3SAT
Creation Date: 1994/11/07
Due Date:      2023/12/31

 A good algorithm will be found for the 3SAT problem, before
 12/31/2020. The problem size S is the sum of the number of variables
 and the number of clauses. The algorithm must run in time less than
 2^(S^.99) on all problems of size S, for all large S. Probabilistic
 algorithms are allowed, if the expected run time on each problem is
 less than the limit. A probabilistic algorithm must get the correct
 answer at least 90% of the time, and each successive run on the same
 problem must further decrease the probability of error by at least
 50%. The algorithm must be available for public inspection 90 days
 prior to judging. The judge may consider empirical evidence,
 especially if a plausible, but unproven, algorithm is offered.

Claim ID:      3VDE
Creation Date: 1995/01/31
Due Date:      2053/12/31

 The problem is to solve every Diophantine Equation in 3 variables. [A 
 Diophantine Equation sets a polynomial with integer coefficients
 equal to 0. In the 3 variable case, P(x,y,z)=0. Solutions x,y,z must
 be integers; negative numbers are allowed. An example of a hard
 Diophantine Equation is x^3 + y^3 + z^3 - 30 = 0.] We want an
 algorithm that, given any such equation, reports the NUMBER of
 solutions (which will sometimes be zero or infinity). By the end of
 the year 2050, either an algorithm will be proven, or the problem
 will be proven undecidable. The conditions of the Claim are the same
 as for the Goldbach Conjecture Claim.

Claim ID:      51St
Creation Date: 1995/11/16
Due Date:      2006/03/01

 By 31 December 2005, at least one new state will have been admitted
 to the United States of America. This claim will be judged true if
 any new state is admitted. This includes a new state on land now part 
 of the US but not now a state, such as the District of Columbia or
 Puerto Rico; the division of a current state into two or more states
 (as allowed in the US constitution); or the admission of new
 territory into the US as a state. New land added as a territory, or a 
 new protectorate or UN trust territory, would not satisfy this claim. 
 (If one or more current states leave, and a new state is later added, 
 the claim will be judged YES: despite the claim abbreviation, the key 
 point is that a state has been added, not the total number of states
 in the US. However, a failed secession attempt, in which the new
 state is the same as a current state, does not count. For the
 purposes of this claim, "now" means 15 November 1995.) If two or more 
 states combine to become a single state, that will not affect this
 claim. 

Claim ID:      AG2000
Creation Date: 1997/03/24
Due Date:      2000/11/30

 This claim will pay $1 if, after a November 2000 general election for 
 the presidency of the United States of America, at least 2 out of the 
 3 following sources report that, based on election returns, Al Gore
 is expected to win the electoral college vote for that election. It
 will pay $0 otherwise, including the case that no November 2000
 general presidential election is held in the US. For purposes of this 
 claim, "Al Gore" is the person who is Vice President of the US as of
 3/24/97.

Claim ID:      APPL
Creation Date: 1995/03/24
Due Date:      2005/01/01

 Apple Computer will cease to exist as a viable corporate entity by 1
 Jan 2005. This claim will be judged YES if at any time before the
 above date Apple Computer a) declares bankruptcy, b) suffers a loss
 in eight consecutive quarters totaling at least one billion dollars,
 or c) has less than a 2.5% market share for new sales of personal
 computers in the United States for a period of at least one year.
 Computers built by Apple running any OS or computers built by other
 companies running any varient of an OS written and sold by Apple
 (i.e., Mac clones) count as Apple market share; computers built by
 other companies and sold with any competing preloaded OS (Any Windows 
 flavor, OS/2, Linux, Amiga OS, etc.) count against market
 share.Should Apple be bought out by another company prior to 1 Jan
 2005, YES and NO shares will each return .50

Claim ID:      ATrB
Creation Date: 1995/04/21
Due Date:      2000/01/01

 A new trading agreement will be formed no later than 1 second after
 midnight, January 1 2000. The agreement need only be signed but not
 ratified by any of the member countries by that date and time. India, 
 China, Japan, Singapore, Taiwan, South Korea, Indonesia, Malaysia,
 and Thailand. There are no restrictions on the number or location of
 any other countries that might join. However, the block of original
 members would hold a majority influence in any organization. Any
 other joining members would be held to a junior membership role.
 There are no restrictions on the member nations, of previous or
 current affiliations in other trade organizations or agreements. Any
 agreement would also restrict the terms of the pact to the signers of 
 the agreement. Any new countries formed within the specified time,
 and in the current borders of the listed member nations should be
 considered seperate nations and invalid from the listed members.

Claim ID:      AUSWAR
Creation Date: 1998/06/09
Due Date:      2050/12/31

 War will be declared on the government of Australia by the government 
 of a foreign country before the end of 2050. This does not preclude a 
 declaration induced by Australia's involvement in a war offshore, or
 by an aggressive military action by any nation whose government is
 recognized by the United Nations, or as a response by such a nation
 to a declaration of war made by the Australian government. Such a
 declaration need not be accompanied by any subsequent or preceding
 military action. If Australia ceases to be an independent nation
 through non-military means before such time, this will be judged in
 the negative.

Claim ID:      AbortX
Creation Date: 1996/08/13
Due Date:      2010/01/15

 This claim shall be judged TRUE if there is a law in the USA that 
 makes first trimester abortion illegal, and someone is convicted  of
 first trimester abortion based on the law between 1996-08-01  and
 2010-01-01.  If there is no such conviction by 2010-01-01, the claim  
 shall be judged FALSE. 
 
 If an appeal is filed within 3 months of the conviction (or of  the
 previous appeal), the result of the appeal  (if before 2010-01-01)
 shall be used to judge the claim.  If a court  refuses to hear the
 appeal, or the conviction has not been overturned by 2010-01-01, the
 claim shall be judged TRUE.  Early TRUE judgement is possible if a
 conviction has exhausted its possibilities for  appeal without being
 overturned, or 3 months have passed without  an appeal being filed. 
 Early FALSE judgement is only  possible if the USA ceases to exist. 
 In no event shall judicial activity on or after 2010-01-01 local time 
 affect the claim result.
 
 For the purposes of this claim, the USA consists of those parts,
 possessions and territories of the United States of America that are
 subject to the USA Constitution and USA Federal law.

Claim ID:      Am30
Creation Date: 1994/11/29
Due Date:      2001/01/02

 By 1 minute past midnight, January 1, 2001, there will be a total of
 (30) or more ratified amendments to the US Constitution, or a new
 constitution will be in the process of ratification. Amendments
 repealing other amendments shall be included in the count. The count
 of thirty shall include all previous amendments, including the Bill
 of Rights.

Claim ID:      Amazon
Creation Date: 1999/01/11
Due Date:      2000/02/02

 
    This claim is a scaled claim based on the price of stock in
    Amazon.com, the online book, movie and gift retailer. It will be
    judged on the stock's closing price on Tuesday, February 1, 2000. YES
    coupons in this claim will pay out an amount equal to:
    
 (Stock price) / 300
 
    where "Stock price" is the value of a single share of stock in
    Amazon.com as purchased on January 15, 1999. If Amazon.com's stock
    splits before this claim's deadline, the claim with be based on the
    total value of all shares held after the split. If Amazon.com is
    aquired by another company before this claim's deadline, the claim
    will be based on the value of whatever compensation would be afforded
    the holder of a single share of stock purchased on January 15, 1999.
    If the value of the share in Amazon.com should meet or exceed $300 at
    the time of the claim's judgement, the claim shall pay out $1 for YES
    coupons.
    
    Amazon.com trades on the Nasdaq exchange with the symbol [1]AMZN. As
    of this claim's writing, the average daily share price was around
    $170, which would result in the paying out of .57 per YES coupon and
    .43 per NO coupon held.
 
 References
 
    1. http://quote.yahoo.com/q?s=AMZN&d=t

Claim ID:      Astr
Creation Date: 1995/04/29
Due Date:      2010/03/15

 
    An exhaustive, repeatable, scientific study will conclude that
    astrology is a statistically significant predictive method to describe
    an individual's personality traits. More specifically, the claim will
    be valid if the following conditions are met:
     1. The astrological method employs any subset of the following
        astronomical, spatial, and/or temporal data as the input variables
        from which the prediction is made.
           + Date of birth, date of conception: the precision is limited
             to one hour.
           + Place of birth, place of conception: the precision is limited
             to a radius of 100 kilometers.
           + The location of astronomical objects, temporally and
             spatially relative to date and place of birth: "astronomical
             object" is limited to the sun, the moon, the planets and
             their moons, the asteroids, comets, and the constellations as
             defined by the standard astrology of western civilization;
             "planets" refers to the planets of the solar system, namely,
             Mercury, Venus, (the Earth), Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus,
             Neptune and Pluto.
     2. A statistically significant correlation is found between a
        astronomical method conforming to the restrictions in (1) and a
        statistically reliable personality measure. "Statistically
        significant correlation" is determined by stochastic measures that
        are widely accepted by the mathematical and statistical academic
        community. "Statistically reliable personality measure" is defined
        as the data contained in and/or the results provided by the
        Minnesota Multi Personality Inventory, or equivalent, as accepted
        by the psychological academic community.
     3. The results of a study conforming with the guidelines of (1) and
        (2) is published by a refereed academic journal, which has broad
        acceptance by the scientific community. Further, the study
        satisfies the usual requirements of exhaustiveness, repeatability,
        and scientific rigor.

Claim ID:      Aurora
Creation Date: 1997/08/20
Due Date:      2002/01/01

 Starting in 1993, there have been rumors of a Mach 6+, air breathing, 
 spyplane nicknamed "Aurora". If the U.S. Air Force (or its successor
 organization) publicly releases information that there is a plane
 matching the description of "Aurora" in its inventory to the New York 
 Times, Washington Post, USA Today, or the Wall Street Journal
 (newsprint editions, and including a photograph of "Aurora" except
 that the Wall Street Journal may have a drawing of "Aurora") the
 claim is YES. Otherwise, the claim is NO.

Claim ID:      AusR
Creation Date: 1995/03/24
Due Date:      2002/01/01

 Australia will, by the end of 2001, cease to be a constitutional
 monarchy under the British Crown. The Constitution will have been
 altered to effect this change and the office of Governor-General, the 
 Queen's representative in the land, will have been replaced by that
 of a Head-of-State chosen either by the people or parliament of
 Australia (or by some other means broadly representative of
 Australian public opinion) who shall have, in law, no higher
 responsibility than to the Commonwealth (or however it may style
 itself by then) of Australia. The new polity may be called the
 Commonwealth, Republic, Sultanate, or anything else, the new
 Head-of-State may be President, Protector or Panjandrum. The country
 may or may not remain within the British Commonwealth of Nations. The 
 claim will be judged YES if, at the time of judgement, Australia has
 severed the formal bond which makes the British monarch and the
 Governor-General a part of the Australian governmental system. The
 claim will be judged NO if either (a) this is not the case, and the
 Governor-General still holds his or her position as laid down by the
 Constitution, or (b) if Australia is no longer demonstrably a
 sovereign nation or recognisable national entity.

Claim ID:      BB2002
Creation Date: 1997/02/07
Due Date:      2003/01/01

 The claim will pay 1.00 on 1/1/2003 if the United States Federal
 Government actual revenues are greater than or equal to its actual
 expenses in fiscal 2002 (i.e. a balance budget or a budget surplus).
 If expenses are greater than revenues (i.e. there is a deficit in
 fiscal 2002), the claim will pay 0.00

Claim ID:      BBQT
Creation Date: 1996/06/11
Due Date:      2005/01/01

 
    "Big Brother" (read U.S. Government) will come to realize by
    01/01/2005 the futility and unreliability of internet censorship. Most
    likely this will be decided in a Supreme Court Decision - a variable
    which impacts on the claim not at all.
    
                  _WHY WOULD THE GOVERNMENT TAKE SUCH A STEP?_
                                       
                              _Perhaps because..._
                                       
    The following are examples of possible causes and or outcomes related
    to the claim and do not represent the actual claim in any other
    fashion then conjecture.
      * Access to internet will become reliant and password protection for
        age validation, allowing those with sufficent resources to track
        individuals and their specific interests.
      * A uncensored U.S. public will be more likely to involve themselves
        in internet activities which could be tracked and used in future
        "blackmail".
      * Off-shore and international internet services will provide
        materials unavailble on "censored" U.S. nets, causing an economic
        imbalance in the market.
      * Crytpography will make enforcement implausible.
      * U.S. Consumers will refuse to pay rising costs of internet access,
        and or taxes so associated with providing censorship.

Claim ID:      BCPrez
Creation Date: 1996/08/28
Due Date:      2001/01/02

 This claim pays $1 for each YES coupon if William Jefferson Clinton
 is still President of the United States at noon (FX server time) on 
 January 1st, 2001.
 
 This claim pays $1 for each NO coupon if William Jefferson Clinton is 
 no longer president of the United States at noon (FX Server Time) on
 January 1st, 2001 for any reason, including but not  restricted to
 loss of election,  declining to run for reelection,  resignation,
 impeachment, or death.
 
 Whether or not Clinton is capable of performing his duties on the 
 judgement date is not relevant to this claim.

Claim ID:      BOOK
Creation Date: 1995/03/16
Due Date:      2020/01/01

 By January 1, 2020, there will be a legal Sports Book operating on US 
 soil, outside the state of Nevada. As of October 1992, Federal Law
 (Public Law No. 102-559) prohibits states which do not already have
 legal sports betting from legalizing it. The only state in which
 there are legal Sports Books is Nevada. For this claim, a Sports Book 
 is a betting etablishment which offers non-Para-mutuel wagers on
 sporting events.
 
  Information on Public Law 102-559 can be obtained through the
 Library of Congress Information Service. (telnet://locis.loc.gov:23/) 
 Search the file for the 102nd congress using the keywords "sports
 wagering".

Claim ID:      BREM
Creation Date: 1995/09/11
Due Date:      2010/01/01

 This claim will pay $1 to every YES vote if by the judging date the
 entirety of the "Elgin Marbles" a collection of pedimental sculpture
 from the Parthenon of Athens, currently housed in the British Museum, 
 are returned to Greece. The Greek Government must have ownership of
 the items. The returning party need not necessarily be the British
 Museum, i.e. theft by the Greek government will count for the
 purposes of this claim. Background: The Elgin Marbles were taken from 
 the Parthenon by Lord Elgin in the 19th century, and placed in the
 British Museum. They are considered by many to be one of the most
 important features of the Acropolis of Athens (were they there). The
 Greek government has demanded their return on several occasions to no 
 avail, and the British government has refused to return them,
 claiming that they are housed and conserved better in Britain.

Claim ID:      BUSH2K
Creation Date: 1999/03/04
Due Date:      2000/12/01

 George W. Bush, son of ex-U.S. president George H.W. Bush, wins the
 U.S. presidential election held in the year 2000.

Claim ID:      BgEU
Creation Date: 1998/02/08
Due Date:      2011/01/01

 This claim will be judged TRUE if, by Jan. 1, 2011, Bulgaria becomes
 a full member of EU. This membership will be recognized only when the 
 necessary agreements are signed by the required parties by the
 indicated date. If, for some reason, EU does not exist on Jan. 1,
 2011, the claim will be judged FALSE.

Claim ID:      Bkhole
Creation Date: 1998/05/17
Due Date:      TBD

 By the end of the next Millenium, a black hole will cause the end of
 life in our part of the galaxy, causing giant disturbation and
 collisions between stars and planets. Earth will become a fire ball
 before being torn in pieces. Hopefully, there will be no life on
 earth at that point....

Claim ID:      BupCan
Creation Date: 1997/06/09
Due Date:      2021/01/01

 Canada as it currently exists will breakup along regional lines by
 2020. No more than 3 of its current provinces will remain part of the 
 Dominion of Canada. For the purposes of this claim, its irrelevant
 whether these regional blocks declare themselves sovereign nations,
 are incorporated into the United States (or another foreign power),
 or are trading partners with any regional area that still refers to
 itself as Canada.
 
 The intent of this claim is that no more than 3 provinces will
 continue to recognize the Federal Government of Canada to have any
 legislative/governing power over them.

Claim ID:      CADE
Creation Date: 1995/05/22
Due Date:      2000/06/01

 
    The Electronic CAD industry of recent years has been dominated by
    three or four large independent vendors with many much smaller
    players. In 1995 the dominant four are [1]Cadence, Mentor Graphics,
    [2]Viewlogic and [3]Synopsys.
    
    The claim is YES if in five year's time there is a European-based
    independent CAD vendor appearing in the top five world sellers of CAD
    software by market share. Market shares will be ascertained from
    DataQuest or other market reports.
    
    Caveats:
     1. Mentor Graphics will be considered a USA-based corporation even if
        their incorporation is moved to the Bahamas as was proposed at one
        point.
     2. The existence of international consortia such as IMEC are
        irrelevant to this claim because they are not independent CAD
        vendors operating in a for-profit mode.
        
    Background:
    
    From: [4]Electronic Engineering Times (Thursday April 27, 1995)
    _Report Urges Europe to Establish Home-Grown EDA vendor_
    By Peter Clarke
    
    BRUSSELS -- Europe should form a world-class systems EDA company to
    compete against Cadence, Mentor Graphics, Viewlogic and Synopsys. If
    necessary, the company should partner with a U.S. vendor to give it
    global reach.
    
    That's one conclusion of a report that has been prepared for the
    European Commission's Directorate General III, which oversees the
    commission's technology initiatives.
    
    The Cornu Report--named after Josef Cornu, chief technologist at
    telecommunications company Alcatel and chairman of the panel that
    produced the study--notes that while publicly funded programs have
    allowed Europe to catch up in basic silicon-processing technology, the
    continent is dependent on U.S. suppliers of CAD tools. The report
    alleges that U.S. EDA vendors' tendency to develop systems-level ideas
    in tandem with U.S.-based customers leaves European systems companies
    out of the decision-making loop.
    
    The study warns that the limited scope of cell libraries and
    licensable cores in Europe will hamper future European
    competitiveness.
    
    "There should be a new European player in the CAD market," the report
    states. "The battle for layout tools must be deemed to have been lost.
    The approach might be for the European semiconductor companies and the
    systems companies to combine as shareholders in a new European
    systems-level CAD company. It would develop and market CAD tools for
    its shareholders and for the open market."
 
 References
 
    1. http://www.cadence.com/
    2. http://www.viewlogic.com/
    3. http://www.synopsys.com/
    4. http://techweb.cmp.com:2090/techweb/eet/current/

Claim ID:      CCx0
Creation Date: 1995/02/28
Due Date:      TBD

 
    The universe is described by a Friedmann-Lemai`tre cosmology in which
    the dimensionless cosmological constant parameter (_Omega_v_) is
    greater than the observed component of the dimensionless mass density
    (_Omega_) to within the accepted uncertainties of both quantities.
    Further information on the cosmological constant is available via WWW
    at the URL: [1]http://www.astro.indiana.edu/personnel/link/CC.html.
 
 References
 
    1. http://www.astro.indiana.edu/personnel/link/CC.html

Claim ID:      CFsn
Creation Date: 1994/09/23
Due Date:      TBD

 
    Cold fusion of deuterium in palladium can produce over 10 watts/cc.
    net power at STP (standard temperature and pressure). Cold fusion is
    discussed on the [1]fusion newsgroup.
 
 References
 
    1. news:sci.physics.fusion

Claim ID:      CLEAST
Creation Date: 1998/09/24
Due Date:      2010/01/01

 The actor Clint Eastwood runs in a Rebublican or Democrat convention
 or as an independent candidate. In a case of running in a convention
 it does not matter if he wins. (to be on the ticket)as long as he
 ran... The claim expires on 01/01/2010 (he will quite old by then)
 
 If he ran but is not on the ticket: claim pays .50 If he is on the
 ticket as would be vice-president: claim pays .75 If he is on the
 ticket as would be president: claim pays 1.00
 
 If he is an independant candidate: claim pays 1.00
 
 and if he is elected...well that is another claim...!
 
 Suntzu

Claim ID:      Canc
Creation Date: 1994/11/07
Due Date:      2014/12/31

 Cancer mortality in the United States will be reduced by 90%,
 relative to 1994, in any year through 2010. (Mortality rates are
 determined by dividing the number of deaths by the population.)
 Cancer includes leukemia, but excludes non-invasive solid tumors, and 
 benign tumors. No adjustments will be made for age-related risk, or
 for reduction or increase in cancer-causing behavior or conditions,
 such as smoking, air pollution, or ozone loss.

Claim ID:      CarC
Creation Date: 1998/05/31
Due Date:      2003/12/31

 Carmichael's Conjecture PROVEN (Carmichael's Conjecture states that
 the value of the Euler phi function, over the domain of all possible
 integers, is never unique)

Claim ID:      Cars
Creation Date: 1996/05/04
Due Date:      2010/12/31

 
    "Intelligent" self-driving road vehicles (defined below) enter
    widespread usage somewhere in the world by the end of 2010.
    
    To qualify for the purposes of this claim, a self-driving vehicle must
    satisfy the following criteria:
     1. It must be reliably able to follow a non-straight road at a speed
        of at least 50 mph (80.5 kph) without input from a human driver.
        Furthermore, this autonomous operation must be legal in the
        state/country in which the vehicle resides.
     2. It must have a passenger/cargo capacity of at least 300 kg.
     3. It must be practically and legally able to travel on roads
        commonly used by cars and trucks and to mingle with normal road
        traffic. However, it need not operate autonomously while doing
        this. Thus, a car which requires an active human driver under most
        conditions, but can operate autonomously on a special highway or
        in a special lane, may qualify for the purposes of the claim.
     4. While driving autonomously, the vehicle may use any sort of
        landmarks or beacons to navigate. However, it may not be towed,
        pushed, pulled, or physically constrained to follow the desired
        path. Thus, a vehicle towed or carried by another vehicle or a
        conveyor belt, or running on rail track, etc., does not qualify.
        
    Autonomous retrofits of previously manufactured non-autonomous
    vehicles may qualify for this claim.
    
    This claim will be judged YES if the judge finds evidence that at
    least 10,000 such vehicles have been manufactured and are in operation
    before December 31, 2010. Otherwise it will be judged NO.

Claim ID:      CatC
Creation Date: 1998/02/09
Due Date:      2003/12/31

 Catalan's Conjecture PROVEN (Catalan's Conjecture states that the
 only two powers (greater than one) of integers, that are one apart,
 are 8 and 9)

Claim ID:      Cent
Creation Date: 1997/03/26
Due Date:      2006/01/01

 The US will produce a one cent coin through the end of 2005. This
 includes any coin by any name worth 1/100th of a US dollar. This coin 
 may be produced directly by the US mint or by another party with the
 authorization of the US treasury.
 
 If, before the claim date, it becomes the official policy of the
 Treasury Department to permanently stop producing the 1 cent coin
 before Jan 1 2006, this claim will be judged FALSE, even if that
 policy is subsequently changed. To judge the claim FALSE, any
 announced stoppage must be intended to be permanent.

Claim ID:      ChBr
Creation Date: 1995/12/01
Due Date:      2002/02/19

 
    After the death of Deng Xiaoping will China remain whole or will the
    provinicial goverments not recognized any clear successor and take the
    opportunity to break into seprate nation states. To answer yes at
    least two portions of China, not counting Taiwan, must have their own,
    unrelated governments. For the answer to be judged yes one of two
    conditions must be met.
     1. The two states recognize no common institute to which they are
        responsible. This condition can occur if one of the two states
        claims independence even if the other state does not recognize it
        as independent. Each government however has to have real control
        over their perpective states. E.g., Taiwan and the Peoples
        Republic of China would count if Taiwan was included.
     2. The two states have a union along the lines of the EU but
        recognize each other as independent and each seek international
        recognition.
        
    The breakup must be clearly defined within five years of Deng
    Xiaopeng's death or after the formation of the country has stabilized,
    whichever comes first. For example if after five years it is unclear
    who is in charge of some portion of China the decision will wait until
    the situation resolves. Furthermore if a new government is formed and
    clearly in power for more than five years after his death any later
    break up does not count.

Claim ID:      ChkS
Creation Date: 1995/01/27
Due Date:      2008/12/31

 The game of Checkers (American style, on an 8x8 board) will be solved 
 by the end of 2005. Either a complete analysis (sufficient to prove a 
 win for one side, or a draw for both), or a mathematically rigorous
 proof of the game value, will be given.

Claim ID:      Clone
Creation Date: 1997/02/24
Due Date:      2006/01/01

 This claim will be judged YES if a clone of an adult (16 years or
 older) human is created and lives to one year of age. Information
 necessary to judge this claim YES must be reported as fact in New
 York Times. 
 
 The clone must live to one year of age prior to January 1, 2005, but
 the report may be published as late as December 31, 2005.
 
 Background: Scientists at the Roslin Institute in Edinburgh, Scotland 
 have created the first clone of an adult mammal, a sheep.
 
 Definition: The definition of clone, as used in this claim, is
 "asexually produced progeny." That is, a new human is created using
 nuclear genetic material from only one parent.

Claim ID:      Coll
Creation Date: 1999/01/24
Due Date:      2020/01/01

 Collatz problem: Take any natural number m > 0
 
 n := m 
 
 Repeat
 
  if n is odd then n:=3*n+1
 
  else n:=n/2 
 
 Until (n==1)
 
 Proof is required that this program terminates after a finite number
 of steps for every natural number m. This proof should be accepted by 
 the mathematics community on or before the judging date.

Claim ID:      Cr28
Creation Date: 1995/08/26
Due Date:      2020/01/14

 
    A cryptographic key of 128 bits or longer will be broken, by
    exhaustively searching the keyspace, before 2010 UT. Keys longer than
    128 bits, but with less than 128 bits of entropy, do not count
    (crippled keys). The results and method of the cracking must be made
    public. This claim makes no attempt to guess what has been done in
    private by governments or other organizations. By "exhaustive" or
    "brute force" search of an N bit key space, I mean the following:
     1. There are 2^N equi-probable decryption keys (1% maximum
        variation), up to 1% can be unused because of weak keys etc.
     2. The actual key must have been generated randomly or from a strong
        hash function.
     3. The keys are tested systematically or randomly, noting only
        whether each key succeed in decrypting the message.
     4. The key must not have been chosen to have any special form
        designed to make this attack easy (e.g. the key 0000...0001). This
        is a judgement call.
        
    On average, the correct key should be found after searching half the
    possible keys. Known plaintext may be used to check the trial
    encryptions. Toy ciphers (in the judge's opinion) do not qualify. This
    is intended to eliminate things like "ROT 13" and simple XOR with a
    constant. Any modern public cipher used in real security applications
    should qualify. IDEA, the symmetrical cipher used by PGP, uses a 128
    bit key.

Claim ID:      Cr80
Creation Date: 1995/08/25
Due Date:      2005/01/14

 A cryptographic key of 80 bits or longer will be broken, by
 exhaustively searching the keyspace, before 2005 UT. Keys longer than 
 80 bits, but with less than 80 bits of entropy, do not count
 (crippled keys). The results and method of the cracking must be made
 public. This claim makes no attempt to guess what has been done in
 private by governments or other organizations. 
 
  "Exhaustive" or "brute force" search defined under Cr28. 
 
  On average, the correct key should be found after searching half the 
 possible keys. Known plaintext may be used to check the trial
 encryptions. 
 
  Toy ciphers (in the judge's opinion) do not qualify. This is
 intended to eliminate things like "ROT 13" and simple XOR with a
 constant. Any modern public cipher used in real security applications 
 should qualify. 
 
  
 
 Skipjack, the crpytosystem in the the US government's proposed
 "Clipper" chips, uses an 80 bit key. Skipjack is also used in the
 Capstone chip on the Fortezza PCMCIA card 

Claim ID:      Cryo
Creation Date: 1994/11/07
Due Date:      2002/12/31

 By December 31, 2000, there will be at least 10,000 persons in
 cryonic suspension. A person who has been revived, but was in
 suspension for at least one year, counts as suspended. Except for
 revivals and attempted revivals, a person removed from suspension
 does not count. Whether a person is suspended or held by a recognized 
 cryonics organization is immaterial. Suspension includes any method
 of pausing or slowing metabolism by at least 90%, including freezing, 
 chemical fixation, suspended animation, high pressure, cooling,
 relativistic time dilation, or any combination. As of October 1994,
 about 55 persons are known to be frozen, some as heads.

Claim ID:      Cybo
Creation Date: 1995/02/17
Due Date:      2036/06/30

 
    At least one human being will be converted to a cyborg by Dec. 31,
    2035. This claim will be true if the resulting construct meets the
    following conditions:
     1. Life support (energy/material supply and waste disposal) met by
        non-original hardware (i.e. heart, lungs, digestive, urinary, &c)
     2. Movement/manipulation provided by non-original hardware
     3. I/O can be either original hardware (e.g. eyes, ears, vocal tract
        left intact) or non-original hardware
     4. CPU can be either original hardware (biological CNS) OR new
        hardware (e.g. "Uploads" - see "suggested claims" page)
     5. The person must be recognized by people previously acquainted with
        it as retaining its original identity ("vegetables" don't count)
     6. The person must be capable of "ordinary" human activities, to be
        judged by the ability to "earn a living" / "contribute to society"
        (becoming a "personality" is OK)

Claim ID:      Cydnia
Creation Date: 1998/04/27
Due Date:      2020/01/01

 
    A main article will be published in Scientific American, Science,
    Archaeology or Nature presenting a non-satiric argument that the
    Cydonia region of Mars contains ancient artificial structures. Some
    sites that deal with the Cydonia region of Mars:
    [1]http://www.sun.com/mars/mgs /target/
    [2]http://www.enterprisemission. com/ [3]http://www.metaresearch.org/
    [4]http://www.psrw.com/~m arkc/marshome.html/
 
 References
 
    1. http://www.sun.com/mars/mgs/target/
    2. http://www.enterprisemission.com/
    3. http://www.metaresearch.org/
    4. http://www.psrw.com/~markc/marshome.html

Claim ID:      DHdt
Creation Date: 1995/10/03
Due Date:      2047/01/15

 This is a scaled claim. YES coupons pay (2047-X)/50, subject to a
 maximum of 1 and a minimum of 0, where X is the first year, 1995 or
 later, in which the Democratic Party controls the U.S. House of
 Representatives. Thus, if Democrats control the House in 1997 or
 sooner, YES coupons pay 1, while if they do not control the House
 until 2047 or later, YES coupons pay 0. 
 
  The Democratic Party is said to control the House of Representatives 
 when there are more Representatives belonging to the Democratic Party 
 than Representatives belonging to all other parties and independents
 combined. Vacant seats are not counted towards this total. 
 
  If the Democratic Party changes its name before it controls the
 House, YES coupons pay 0. 
 
  Note that at the time of creation of this claim, members of the U.S. 
 House elected in November do not take their seats until the following 
 January. Thus, (barring any changes to this procedure), if Democrats
 first won control of the House in the November 2006 election, they
 would not actually have control until January 2007, and YES coupons
 would therefore pay 0.80, and not 0.82.

Claim ID:      DJIA
Creation Date: 1999/02/22
Due Date:      2000/01/10

 Yes coupons shall pay (DJIA-6500)/50 rounded to the nearest cent (but 
 not less than zero nor more than 100) where DJIA is the last closing
 value of the Dow Jones Industrial Average for the year 1999, as
 published by Dow Jones.

